  "local_port": 59458,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "When I eat sushi, what is the eel sauce made of?",
  "response": "Eel sauce, commonly referred to as **unagi sauce** or **kabayaki sauce**, is a popular condiment in Japanese cuisine, especially used to enhance dishes like unagi (grilled eel) sushi. Despite its name, eel sauce typically **does not contain eel**. Instead, it's a **sweet and savory** sauce that complements the rich flavors of grilled eel and other dishes. Here's what eel sauce is typically made of:\n\n### **Primary Ingredients:**\n\n1. **Soy Sauce:**\n   - **Role:** Acts as the salty, umami-rich base of the sauce.\n   - **Type:** Dark soy sauce is often preferred for its robust flavor.\n\n2. **Mirin:**\n   - **Role:** A sweet Japanese rice wine that adds sweetness and depth.\n   - **Note:** Mirin also helps in balancing the saltiness of the soy sauce.\n\n3. **Sugar:**\n   - **Role:** Enhances the sweetness and contributes to the sauce's thick, syrupy consistency.\n   - **Type:** Granulated white sugar is commonly used, but some recipes may use alternative sweeteners.\n\n4. **Sake** (Optional):\n   - **Role:** Adds complexity and depth to the flavor profile.\n   - **Note:** Sake can also aid in tenderizing proteins if the sauce is used as a marinade.\n\n### **Preparation Method:**\n\n1. **Combine Ingredients:**\n   - Mix **soy sauce**, **mirin**, **sugar**, and optionally **sake** in a saucepan. A common ratio to start with is 1:1:0.5:0.5 (soy sauce:mirin:sugar:sake), but this can be adjusted based on desired sweetness and thickness.\n\n2. **Simmer:**\n   - Heat the mixture over medium heat, stirring continuously to dissolve the sugar completely.\n\n3. **Reduce:**\n   - Allow the sauce to simmer until it reduces by about half, thickening to a glossy, syrup-like consistency. This usually takes about 10-15 minutes.\n\n4. **Cool:**\n   - Remove from heat and let the sauce cool. It will continue to thicken slightly as it cools.\n\n### **Additional Ingredients (Optional):**\n\n- **Grated Ginger or Garlic:** For added aromatic depth.\n- **Cornstarch Slurry:** Sometimes used to achieve a thicker consistency, although traditional methods rely on reduction.\n\n### **Usage:**\n\n- **Drizzling:** Commonly drizzled over grilled eel (unagi) or other sushi rolls.\n- **Marinades:** Used to marinate proteins like eel before grilling.\n- **Glazing:** Applied as a glaze for various grilled or steamed dishes.\n\n### **Storage:**\n\n- Eel sauce can be stored in an airtight container in the refrigerator for several weeks. Its flavors may develop further over time.\n\n### **Note:**\n\nWhile homemade eel sauce allows you to adjust sweetness and thickness to your preference, it's also widely available commercially. Brands like **Kikkoman** and **Eel Sauce** offer ready-made versions that are convenient for everyday use.\n\n---\n\n**Quick Homemade Eel Sauce Recipe:**\n\n**Ingredients:**\n- 1/2 cup soy sauce\n- 1/2 cup mirin\n- 1/4 cup sugar\n- 1/4 cup sake (optional)\n\n**Instructions:**\n1. Combine all ingredients in a saucepan.\n2. Bring to a gentle boil, stirring to dissolve the sugar.\n3. Reduce heat and let simmer until the sauce thickens to your desired consistency.\n4. Remove from heat and let cool before using or storing.\n\nEnjoy your sushi with this rich and flavorful eel sauce!",
